    <!-- Key Design Decisions -->
    <section class="decisions-section">
      <h2>⚖️ Key Design Decisions</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Every video streaming system involves critical tradeoffs. Click each card to explore the considerations.</p>
      <div class="decisions-grid">
        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="latency-quality">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <span class="decision-icon">⏱️</span>
            <h4>Latency vs Quality</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Low Latency</strong>
              <p>Smaller buffers, aggressive ABR downshift. Risk: more rebuffering, quality fluctuation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-vs">vs</div>
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>High Quality</strong>
              <p>Larger buffers (30s+), conservative quality switches. Risk: slow startup, stale content for live.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-verdict">Most services use a hybrid: aggressive startup, then shift to quality-optimizing mode once buffer is healthy.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="storage-compute">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <span class="decision-icon">💾</span>
            <h4>Storage vs Compute</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Pre-encode All</strong>
              <p>Encode every resolution upfront. Fast delivery, high storage cost. Good for popular content.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-vs">vs</div>
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Just-in-Time</strong>
              <p>Encode on demand. Low storage, high compute latency. Good for long-tail content rarely watched.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-verdict">Tiered approach: popular content pre-encoded at all tiers; long-tail content encoded at 2-3 tiers, rest on-demand.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="push-pull">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <span class="decision-icon">🔄</span>
            <h4>Push vs Pull CDN</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Push CDN</strong>
              <p>Origin pushes content to edges proactively. Predictable performance, higher bandwidth cost.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-vs">vs</div>
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Pull CDN</strong>
              <p>Edge pulls from origin on cache miss. Lower cost, risk of cold-start latency for first viewer.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-verdict">Hybrid: push to top-tier PoPs for new/trending content; pull for everything else. Pre-warm edges for scheduled releases.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="hls-dash">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <span class="decision-icon">📄</span>
            <h4>HLS vs DASH</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>HLS (Apple)</strong>
              <p>Native iOS/Safari. TS or fMP4 segments. Mature ecosystem. Required for Apple devices.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-vs">vs</div>
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>DASH (MPEG)</strong>
              <p>Open standard. fMP4 segments. More flexible. Better DRM integration. Preferred on Android/Web.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-verdict">Most services support both via CMAF (Common Media Application Format) — same fMP4 segments, different manifests.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="monolith-micro">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <span class="decision-icon">🏛️</span>
            <h4>Monolith vs Microservices</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Monolith</strong>
              <p>Simpler deployment, single codebase. Harder to scale individual components independently.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-vs">vs</div>
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>Microservices</strong>
              <p>Independent scaling (transcoding vs API vs search). Complex orchestration, network overhead.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-verdict">Microservices win at scale: transcoding, CDN, API, search, recommendations each scale independently with different resource profiles.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="codec">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <span class="decision-icon">🎞️</span>
            <h4>H.264 vs H.265 vs AV1</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>H.264 (AVC)</strong>
              <p>Universal support. Lower compression. Fast encoding. Patent licensed but ubiquitous.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-vs">vs</div>
            <div class="decision-option">
              <strong>AV1</strong>
              <p>30-50% better compression. Royalty-free. Slow encoding (10-100x). Growing hardware decode support.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-verdict">Ladder approach: AV1 for popular content (amortize encode cost), H.264 as fallback for compatibility, H.265 for mobile/4K.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

